[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Exponential smoothing is one of many window functions commonly applied to smooth data in signal processing, acting as low-pass filters to remove high-frequency noise.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] This method is preceded by Poisson's use of recursive exponential window functions in convolutions from the 19th century, as well as Kolmogorov and Zurbenko's use of recursive moving averages from their studies of turbulence in the 1940s.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] where ${\textstyle \alpha }$ is the *smoothing factor*, and ${\textstyle 0<\alpha <1}$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] The use of the exponential window function is first attributed to Poisson as an extension of a numerical analysis technique from the 17th century, and later adopted by the signal processing community in the 1940s.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Here, exponential smoothing is the application of the exponential, or Poisson, window function.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Exponential smoothing was suggested in the statistical literature without citation to previous work by Robert Goodell Brown in 1956, and expanded by Charles C.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] The formulation below, which is the one commonly used, is attributed to Brown and is known as "Brown’s simple exponential smoothing".
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] All the methods of Holt, Winters, and Brown may be seen as a simple application of recursive filtering, first found in the 1940s to convert finite impulse response (FIR) filters to infinite impulse response filters.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] where $\alpha$ is the *smoothing factor*, with $0\leq \alpha \leq 1$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] In other words, the smoothed statistic $s_{t}$ is a simple weighted average of the current observation $x_{t}$ and the previous smoothed statistic $s_{t-1}$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Simple exponential smoothing is easily applied, and it produces a smoothed statistic as soon as two observations are available.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] The term *smoothing factor* applied to $\alpha$ here is something of a misnomer, as larger values of $\alpha$ actually reduce the level of smoothing, and in the limiting case with $\alpha$ = 1 the smoothing output series is just the current observation.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Values of $\alpha$ close to 1 have less of a smoothing effect and give greater weight to recent changes in the data, while values of $\alpha$ closer to 0 have a greater smoothing effect and are less responsive to recent changes.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] In the limiting case with $\alpha$ = 0, the output series is just flat or a constant as the observation ${\textstyle x_{0}}$ at the beginning of the smoothening process ${\textstyle t=0}$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] The method for choosing $\alpha$ must be decided by the modeler.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Sometimes the statistician's judgment is used to choose an appropriate factor.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Alternatively, a statistical technique may be used to *optimize* the value of $\alpha$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] For example, the method of least squares might be used to determine the value of $\alpha$ for which the sum of the quantities $(s_{t}-x_{t+1})^{2}$ is minimized.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Unlike some other smoothing methods, such as the simple moving average, this technique does not require any minimum number of observations to be made before it begins to produce results.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] In practice, however, a "good average" will not be achieved until several samples have been averaged together; for example, a constant signal will take approximately $3/\alpha$ stages to reach 95% of the actual value.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] To accurately reconstruct the original signal without information loss, all stages of the exponential moving average must also be available, because older samples decay in weight exponentially.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] This is in contrast to a simple moving average, in which some samples can be skipped without as much loss of information due to the constant weighting of samples within the average.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] If a known number of samples will be missed, one can adjust a weighted average for this as well, by giving equal weight to the new sample and all those to be skipped.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] This simple form of exponential smoothing is also known as an exponentially weighted moving average (EWMA).
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Technically it can also be classified as an autoregressive integrated moving average (ARIMA) (0,1,1) model with no constant term.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] The time constant of an exponential moving average is the amount of time for the smoothed response of a unit step function to reach $1-1/e\approx 63.2\,\%$ of the final signal.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] where $\Delta T$ is the sampling time interval of the discrete time implementation.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Note that in the definition above, $s_{0}$ (the initial output of the exponential smoothing algorithm) is being initialized to $x_{0}$ (the initial raw data or observation).
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Because exponential smoothing requires that, at each stage, we have the previous forecast $s_{t-1}$ , it is not obvious how to get the method started.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] We could assume that the initial forecast is equal to the initial value of demand; however, this approach has a serious drawback.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Exponential smoothing puts substantial weight on past observations, so the initial value of demand will have an unreasonably large effect on early forecasts.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] This problem can be overcome by allowing the process to evolve for a reasonable number of periods (10 or more) and using the average of the demand during those periods as the initial forecast.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] There are many other ways of setting this initial value, but the smaller the value of $\alpha$ , the more sensitive the forecast will be on the selection of this initial smoother value $s_{0}$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] For every exponential smoothing method, we also need to choose the value for the smoothing parameters.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] For simple exponential smoothing, there is only one smoothing parameter (*α*), but for the methods that follow there are usually more than one smoothing parameter.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] There are cases where the smoothing parameters may be chosen in a subjective manner – the forecaster specifies the value of the smoothing parameters based on previous experience.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] However, a more robust and objective way to obtain values of the unknown parameters included in any exponential smoothing method is to estimate them from the observed data.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] The unknown parameters and the initial values for any exponential smoothing method can be estimated by minimizing the sum of squared errors (SSE).
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Unlike the regression case (where we have formulae to directly compute the regression coefficients which minimize the SSE) this involves a non-linear minimization problem, and we need to use an optimization tool to perform this.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] The name *exponential smoothing* is attributed to the use of the exponential function as the filter impulse response in the convolution.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] A geometric progression is the discrete version of an exponential function, so this is where the name for this smoothing method originated according to Statistics lore.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Exponential smoothing and moving average have similar defects of introducing a lag relative to the input data.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] While this can be corrected by shifting the result by half the window length for a symmetrical kernel, such as a moving average or gaussian, this approach is not possible for exponential smoothing since it is an IIR filter and therefore has an asymmetric kernel and frequency-dependent group delay.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] This means each constituent frequency is shifted by a different amount and therefore, there is no single number of samples that can be used to shift the output signal to account for the lag.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Both filters also both have roughly the same distribution of forecast error when *α* = 2/(*k* + 1) where *k* is the number of past data points in consideration of moving average.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] They differ in that exponential smoothing takes into account all past data, whereas moving average only takes into account *k* past data points.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Computationally speaking, they also differ in that moving average requires that the past *k* data points, or the data point at lag *k* + 1 plus the most recent forecast value, to be kept, whereas exponential smoothing only needs the most recent forecast value to be kept.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Simple exponential smoothing does not do well when there is a trend in the data.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] In such situations, several methods were devised under the name "double exponential smoothing" or "second-order exponential smoothing," which is the recursive application of an exponential filter twice, thus being termed "double exponential smoothing".
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] The basic idea behind double exponential smoothing is to introduce a term to take into account the possibility of a series exhibiting some form of trend.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] This slope component is itself updated via exponential smoothing.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Again, the raw data sequence of observations is represented by $x_{t}$ , beginning at time $t=0$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] We use $s_{t}$ to represent the smoothed value for time t , and $b_{t}$ is our best estimate of the trend at time t .
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] The output of the algorithm is now written as $F_{t+m}$ , an estimate of the value of $x_{t+m}$ at time $m>0$ based on the raw data up to time t .
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] where $\alpha$ ( $0\leq \alpha \leq 1$ ) is the *data smoothing factor*, and $\beta$ ( $0\leq \beta \leq 1$ ) is the *trend smoothing factor*.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Setting the initial value b is a matter of preference.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] An option other than the one listed above is ${\textstyle {\frac {x_{n}-x_{0}}{n}}}$ for some n .
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Note that *F*0 is undefined (there is no estimation for time 0), and according to the definition *F*1=*s*0+*b*0, which is well defined, thus further values can be evaluated.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Triple exponential smoothing applies exponential smoothing three times, which is commonly used when there are three high frequency signals to be removed from a time series under study.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] There are different types of seasonality: 'multiplicative' and 'additive' in nature.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Multiplicative signifies that the seasonal effect size depends on the current level, while additive seasonal effects do not.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] If in *every* summer we sell 10,000 more balls of ice cream than we do in winter, then seasonality is *additive*.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] However, if we sell 6 times more ice cream in summer than in winter, that means that the difference in sales amounts moves together with the level itself: in years with overall larger consumption, the difference between summer and winter is larger and vice versa.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Multiplicative seasonality can be represented as a constant factor, additive seasonality as an absolute amount.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Triple exponential smoothing was first suggested by Holt's student, Peter Winters, in 1960 after reading a signal processing book from the 1940s on exponential smoothing.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Holt's novel idea was to repeat filtering an odd number of times greater than 1 and less than 5, which was popular with scholars of previous eras.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] While recursive filtering had been used previously, it was applied twice and four times to coincide with the Hadamard conjecture, while triple application required more than double the operations of singular convolution.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] The use of a triple application is considered a rule of thumb technique, rather than one based on theoretical foundations and has often been overemphasized by practitioners.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Suppose we have a sequence of observations $x_{t},$ beginning at time $t=0$ with a cycle of seasonal change of length L .
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] The method calculates a trend line for the data as well as seasonal indices that weight the values in the trend line based on where that time point falls in the cycle of length L .
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Let $s_{t}$ represent the smoothed value of the constant part for time t , $b_{t}$ is the sequence of best estimates of the linear trend that are superimposed on the seasonal changes, and $c_{t}$ is the sequence of seasonal correction factors.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] We wish to estimate $c_{t}$ at every time t mod L in the cycle that the observations take on.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] As a rule of thumb, a minimum of two full seasons (or $2L$ periods) of historical data is needed to initialize a set of seasonal factors.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] The output of the algorithm is again written as $F_{t+m}$ , an estimate of the value of $x_{t+m}$ at time $t+m>0$ based on the raw data up to time t .
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] where $\alpha$ ( $0\leq \alpha \leq 1$ ) is the *data smoothing factor*, $\beta$ ( $0\leq \beta \leq 1$ ) is the *trend smoothing factor*, and $\gamma$ ( $0\leq \gamma \leq 1$ ) is the *seasonal change smoothing factor*.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Setting the initial estimates for the seasonal indices $c_{i}$ for $i=1,2,\ldots ,L$ is a bit more involved.
[src:adam-optimizer/exponential-smoothing] Note that $A_{j}$ is the average value of x in the $j^{\text{th}}$ cycle of your data.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] In machine learning, a **hyperparameter** is a parameter that can be set in order to define any configurable part of a model's learning process.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Hyperparameters can be classified as either model hyperparameters (such as the topology and size of a neural network) or algorithm hyperparameters (such as the learning rate and the batch size of an optimizer).
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] These are named *hyper*parameters in contrast to parameters, which are characteristics that the model learns from the data.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Hyperparameters are not required by every model or algorithm.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Some simple algorithms such as ordinary least squares regression require none.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] However, the LASSO algorithm, for example, adds a regularization hyperparameter to ordinary least squares which must be set before training.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Even models and algorithms without a strict requirement to define hyperparameters may not produce meaningful results if these are not carefully chosen.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] However, optimal values for hyperparameters are not always easy to predict.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Some hyperparameters may have no meaningful effect, or one important variable may be conditional upon the value of another.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Often a separate process of hyperparameter tuning is needed to find a suitable combination for the data and task.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] As well as improving model performance, hyperparameters can be used by researchers to introduce robustness and reproducibility into their work, especially if it uses models that incorporate random number generation.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] The time required to train and test a model can depend upon the choice of its hyperparameters.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] A hyperparameter is usually of continuous or integer type, leading to mixed-type optimization problems.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] The existence of some hyperparameters is conditional upon the value of others, e.g. the size of each hidden layer in a neural network can be conditional upon the number of layers.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] The objective function is typically non-differentiable with respect to hyperparameters.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] As a result, in most instances, hyperparameters cannot be learned using gradient-based optimization methods (such as gradient descent), which are commonly employed to learn model parameters.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] These hyperparameters are those parameters describing a model representation that cannot be learned by common optimization methods, but nonetheless affect the loss function.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] An example would be the tolerance hyperparameter for errors in support vector machines.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Sometimes, hyperparameters cannot be learned from the training data because they aggressively increase the capacity of a model and can push the loss function to an undesired minimum (overfitting to the data), as opposed to correctly mapping the richness of the structure in the data.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] For example, if we treat the degree of a polynomial equation fitting a regression model as a trainable parameter, the degree would increase until the model perfectly fit the data, yielding low training error, but poor generalization performance.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Most performance variation can be attributed to just a few hyperparameters.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] The tunability of an algorithm, hyperparameter, or interacting hyperparameters is a measure of how much performance can be gained by tuning it.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] For an LSTM, while the learning rate followed by the network size are its most crucial hyperparameters, batching and momentum have no significant effect on its performance.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Although some research has advocated the use of mini-batch sizes in the thousands, other work has found the best performance with mini-batch sizes between 2 and 32.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] An inherent stochasticity in learning directly implies that the empirical hyperparameter performance is not necessarily its true performance.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Methods that are not robust to simple changes in hyperparameters, random seeds, or even different implementations of the same algorithm cannot be integrated into mission critical control systems without significant simplification and robustification.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Reinforcement learning algorithms, in particular, require measuring their performance over a large number of random seeds, and also measuring their sensitivity to choices of hyperparameters.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Their evaluation with a small number of random seeds does not capture performance adequately due to high variance.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Some reinforcement learning methods, e.g.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] DDPG (Deep Deterministic Policy Gradient), are more sensitive to hyperparameter choices than others.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Hyperparameter optimization finds a tuple of hyperparameters that yields an optimal model which minimizes a predefined loss function on given test data.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] The objective function takes a tuple of hyperparameters and returns the associated loss.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Typically these methods are not gradient based, and instead apply concepts from derivative-free optimization or black box optimization.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Apart from tuning hyperparameters, machine learning involves storing and organizing the parameters and results, and making sure they are reproducible.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] In the absence of a robust infrastructure for this purpose, research code often evolves quickly and compromises essential aspects like bookkeeping and reproducibility.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Online collaboration platforms for machine learning go further by allowing scientists to automatically share, organize and discuss experiments, data, and algorithms.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] Reproducibility can be particularly difficult for deep learning models.
[src:adam-optimizer/hyperparameter-machine-learning] For example, research has shown that deep learning models depend very heavily even on the random seed selection of the random number generator.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] In machine learning and statistics, the **learning rate** is a tuning parameter in an optimization algorithm that determines the step size at each iteration while moving toward a minimum of a loss function.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] Since it influences to what extent newly acquired information overrides old information, it metaphorically represents the speed at which a machine learning model "learns".
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] In the adaptive control literature, the learning rate is commonly referred to as **gain**.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] In setting a learning rate, there is a trade-off between the rate of convergence and overshooting.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] While the descent direction is usually determined from the gradient of the loss function, the learning rate determines how big a step is taken in that direction.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] Too high a learning rate will make the learning jump over minima, but too low a learning rate will either take too long to converge or get stuck in an undesirable local minimum.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] In order to achieve faster convergence, prevent oscillations and getting stuck in undesirable local minima the learning rate is often varied during training either in accordance to a learning rate schedule or by using an adaptive learning rate.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] The learning rate and its adjustments may also differ per parameter, in which case it is a diagonal matrix that can be interpreted as an approximation to the inverse of the Hessian matrix in Newton's method.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] The learning rate is related to the step length determined by inexact line search in quasi-Newton methods and related optimization algorithms.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] Initial rate can be left as system default or can be selected using a range of techniques.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] A learning rate schedule changes the learning rate during learning and is most often changed between epochs/iterations.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] This is mainly done with two parameters: **decay** and **momentum**.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] There are many different learning rate schedules but the most common are **time-based, step-based** and **exponential**.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] where $\eta$ is the learning rate, $\eta _{0}$ is the original learning rate, d is a decay parameter and n is the iteration step.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] The *floor* function ( $\lfloor \dots \rfloor$ ) here drops the value of its input to 0 for all values smaller than 1.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] The issue with learning rate schedules is that they all depend on hyperparameters that must be manually chosen for each given learning session and may vary greatly depending on the problem at hand or the model used.
[src:adam-optimizer/learning-rate] To combat this, there are many different types of adaptive gradient descent algorithms such as Adagrad, Adadelta, RMSprop, and Adam which are generally built into deep learning libraries such as Keras.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In mathematical optimization and decision theory, a **loss function** or **cost function** (sometimes also called an error function) is a function that maps an event or values of one or more variables onto a real number intuitively representing some "cost" associated with the event.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] An optimization problem seeks to minimize a loss function.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] An **objective function** is either a loss function or its opposite (in specific domains, variously called a reward function, a profit function, a utility function, a fitness function, etc.), in which case it is to be maximized.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] The loss function could include terms from several levels of the hierarchy.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In statistics, typically a loss function is used for parameter estimation, and the event in question is some function of the difference between estimated and true values for an instance of data.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] The concept, as old as Laplace, was reintroduced in statistics by Abraham Wald in the middle of the 20th century.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In the context of economics, for example, this is usually economic cost or regret.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In classification, it is the penalty for an incorrect classification of an example.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In actuarial science, it is used in an insurance context to model benefits paid over premiums, particularly since the works of Harald Cramér in the 1920s.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In optimal control, the loss is the penalty for failing to achieve a desired value.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In financial risk management, the function is mapped to a monetary loss.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] The use of a quadratic loss function is common, for example when using least squares techniques.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] It is often more mathematically tractable than other loss functions because of the properties of variances, as well as being symmetric: an error above the target causes the same loss as the same magnitude of error below the target.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] for some constant C ; the value of the constant makes no difference to a decision, and can be ignored by setting it equal to 1.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] This is also known as the **squared error loss** (**SEL**).
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Many common statistics, including t-tests, regression models, design of experiments, and much else, use least squares methods applied using linear regression theory, which is based on the quadratic loss function.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] The quadratic loss function is also used in linear-quadratic optimal control problems.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In these problems, even in the absence of uncertainty, it may not be possible to achieve the desired values of all target variables.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Often loss is expressed as a quadratic form in the deviations of the variables of interest from their desired values; this approach is tractable because it results in linear first-order conditions.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In the context of stochastic control, the expected value of the quadratic form is used.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] The quadratic loss assigns more importance to outliers than to the true data due to its square nature, so alternatives like the Huber, log-cosh and SMAE losses are used when the data has many large outliers.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In information theory, this loss function is known as Hamming distortion.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In many applications, objective functions, including loss functions as a particular case, are determined by the problem formulation.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In other situations, the decision maker’s preference must be elicited and represented by a scalar-valued function (called also utility function) in a form suitable for optimization — the problem that Ragnar Frisch has highlighted in his Nobel Prize lecture.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] The existing methods for constructing objective functions are collected in the proceedings of two dedicated conferences.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In particular, Andranik Tangian showed that the most usable objective functions — quadratic and additive — are determined by a few indifference points.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] He used this property in the models for constructing these objective functions from either ordinal or cardinal data that were elicited through computer-assisted interviews with decision makers.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Among other things, he constructed objective functions to optimally distribute budgets for 16 Westfalian universities and the European subsidies for equalizing unemployment rates among 271 German regions.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In some contexts, the value of the loss function itself is a random quantity because it depends on the outcome of a random variable X .
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Both frequentist and Bayesian statistical theory involve making a decision based on the expected value of the loss function; however, this quantity is defined differently under the two paradigms.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] We first define the expected loss in the frequentist context.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] It is obtained by taking the expected value with respect to the probability distribution, $P_{\theta }$ , of the observed data, X .
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] This is also referred to as the **risk function** of the decision rule $\delta$ and the parameter $\theta$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Here the decision rule depends on the outcome of X .
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] where $M(\mathbf {x} )$ is known as the *predictive likelihood* wherein $\theta$ has been "integrated out," $\pi ^{*}(\theta |\mathbf {x} )$ is the posterior distribution, and the order of integration has been changed.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] One then should choose the action $a^{*}$ which minimises this expected loss, which is referred to as *Bayes Risk*.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In the latter equation, the integrand inside $\mathrm {d} x$ is known as the *Posterior Risk*, and minimising it with respect to decision a also minimizes the overall Bayes Risk.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] This optimal decision, $a^{*}$ is known as the *Bayes (decision) Rule* - it minimises the average loss over all possible states of nature $\theta$ , over all possible (probability-weighted) data outcomes.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] One advantage of the Bayesian approach is to that one need only choose the optimal action under the actual observed data to obtain a uniformly optimal one, whereas choosing the actual frequentist optimal decision rule as a function of all possible observations, is a much more difficult problem.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Of equal importance though, the Bayes Rule reflects consideration of loss outcomes under different states of nature, $\theta$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In economics, decision-making under uncertainty is often modelled using the von Neumann–Morgenstern utility function of the uncertain variable of interest, such as end-of-period wealth.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Since the value of this variable is uncertain, so is the value of the utility function; it is the expected value of utility that is maximized.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] A decision rule makes a choice using an optimality criterion.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Sound statistical practice requires selecting an estimator consistent with the actual acceptable variation experienced in the context of a particular applied problem.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Thus, in the applied use of loss functions, selecting which statistical method to use to model an applied problem depends on knowing the losses that will be experienced from being wrong under the problem's particular circumstances.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] A common example involves estimating "location".
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Still different estimators would be optimal under other, less common circumstances.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In economics, when an agent is risk neutral, the objective function is simply expressed as the expected value of a monetary quantity, such as profit, income, or end-of-period wealth.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] For risk-averse or risk-loving agents, loss is measured as the negative of a utility function, and the objective function to be optimized is the expected value of utility.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Other measures of cost are possible, for example mortality or morbidity in the field of public health or safety engineering.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] For most optimization algorithms, it is desirable to have a loss function that is globally continuous and differentiable.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Two very commonly used loss functions are the squared loss, $L(a)=a^{2}$ , and the absolute loss, $L(a)=|a|$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] However the absolute loss has the disadvantage that it is not differentiable at $a=0$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] The squared loss has the disadvantage that it has the tendency to be dominated by outliers—when summing over a set of a 's (as in ${\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{n}L(a_{i})}$ ), the final sum tends to be the result of a few particularly large a -values, rather than an expression of the average a -value.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] The choice of a loss function is not arbitrary.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] It is very restrictive and sometimes the loss function may be characterized by its desirable properties.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Among the choice principles are, for example, the requirement of completeness of the class of symmetric statistics in the case of i.i.d. observations, the principle of complete information, and some others.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Edwards Deming and Nassim Nicholas Taleb argue that empirical reality, not nice mathematical properties, should be the sole basis for selecting loss functions, and real losses often are not mathematically nice and are not differentiable, continuous, symmetric, etc.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] For example, a person who arrives before a plane gate closure can still make the plane, but a person who arrives after cannot, a discontinuity and asymmetry which makes arriving slightly late much more costly than arriving slightly early.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] In drug dosing, the cost of too little drug may be lack of efficacy, while the cost of too much may be tolerable toxicity, another example of asymmetry.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] Traffic, pipes, beams, ecologies, climates, etc. may tolerate increased load or stress with little noticeable change up to a point, then become backed up or break catastrophically.
[src:adam-optimizer/loss-function] These situations, Deming and Taleb argue, are common in real-life problems, perhaps more common than classical smooth, continuous, symmetric, differentials cases.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] For a distribution of mass or probability on a bounded interval, the collection of all the moments (of all orders, from 0 to ∞) uniquely determines the distribution (Hausdorff moment problem).
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The same is not true on unbounded intervals (Hamburger moment problem).
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] In the mid-nineteenth century, Pafnuty Chebyshev became the first person to think systematically in terms of the moments of random variables.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] It is possible to define moments for random variables in a more general fashion than moments for real-valued functions – see moments in metric spaces.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The moment of a function, without further explanation, usually refers to the above expression with $c=0$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] For the second and higher moments, the central moment (moments about the mean, with *c* being the mean) are usually used rather than the moments about zero, because they provide clearer information about the distribution's shape.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The nth moment about zero of a probability density function $f(x)$ is the expected value of $X^{n}$ and is called a *raw moment* or *crude moment* or *population moment* or *uncorrected moment*.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The moments about its mean $\mu$ are called *central* moments; these describe the shape of the function, independently of translation.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] If f is a probability density function, then the value of the integral above is called the nth moment of the probability distribution.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] When $\operatorname {E} \left[\left|X^{n}\right|\right]=\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }\left|x^{n}\right|\,\mathrm {d} F(x)=\infty$ the moment is said not to exist.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] If the nth moment about any point exists, so does the (*n* − 1)th moment (and thus, all lower-order moments) about every point.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The zeroth moment of any probability density function is 1, since the area under any probability density function must be equal to one.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] These normalised central moments are dimensionless quantities, which represent the distribution independently of any linear change of scale.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The second central moment is the variance.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The third central moment is the measure of the lopsidedness of the distribution; any symmetric distribution will have a third central moment, if defined, of zero.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The normalised third central moment is called the skewness, often γ.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] A distribution that is skewed to the left (the tail of the distribution is longer on the left) will have a negative skewness.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] A distribution that is skewed to the right (the tail of the distribution is longer on the right), will have a positive skewness.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] For distributions that are not too different from the normal distribution, the median will be somewhere near *μ* − *γσ*/6; the mode about *μ* − *γσ*/2.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The fourth central moment is a measure of the heaviness of the tail of the distribution.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] Since it is the expectation of a fourth power, the fourth central moment, where defined, is always nonnegative; and except for a point distribution, it is always strictly positive.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The fourth central moment of a normal distribution is 3*σ*4.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The kurtosis κ is defined to be the standardized fourth central moment.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The kurtosis can be positive without limit, but κ must be greater than or equal to *γ*2 + 1; equality only holds for binary distributions.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] For unbounded skew distributions not too far from normal, κ tends to be somewhere in the area of *γ*2 and 2*γ*2.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] This is the expectation of a square, so it is non-negative for all *a*; however it is also a quadratic polynomial in *a*.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] Its discriminant must be non-positive, which gives the required relationship.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] As with variance, skewness, and kurtosis, these are higher-order statistics, involving non-linear combinations of the data, and can be used for description or estimation of further shape parameters.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The higher the moment, the harder it is to estimate, in the sense that larger samples are required in order to obtain estimates of similar quality.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] This is due to the excess degrees of freedom consumed by the higher orders.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] Further, they can be subtle to interpret, often being most easily understood in terms of lower order moments – compare the higher-order derivatives of jerk and jounce in physics.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The value $E[X^{k}]$ is called the moment of order k (moments are also defined for non-integral k ).
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The moments of the joint distribution of random variables $X_{1}...X_{n}$ are defined similarly.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The mixed moment $E[(X_{1}-E[X_{1}])(X_{2}-E[X_{2}])]$ is called the covariance and is one of the basic characteristics of dependency between random variables.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] Some examples are covariance, coskewness and cokurtosis.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] While there is a unique covariance, there are multiple co-skewnesses and co-kurtoses.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] This identity follows by the convolution theorem for moment generating function and applying the chain rule for differentiating a product.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] (These can also hold for variables that satisfy weaker conditions than independence.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The first always holds; if the second holds, the variables are called uncorrelated).
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] These are the first three cumulants and all cumulants share this additivity property.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] For all *k*, the kth raw moment of a population can be estimated using the kth raw sample moment ${\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}X_{i}^{k}$ applied to a sample *X*1, ..., *Xn* drawn from the population.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] It can be shown that the expected value of the raw sample moment is equal to the kth raw moment of the population, if that moment exists, for any sample size n.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] This contrasts with the situation for central moments, whose computation uses up a degree of freedom by using the sample mean.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] This estimate of the population moment is greater than the unadjusted observed sample moment by a factor of ${\tfrac {n}{n-1}},$ and it is referred to as the "adjusted sample variance" or sometimes simply the "sample variance".
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] Problems of determining a probability distribution from its sequence of moments are called *problem of moments*.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] Such problems were first discussed by P.L.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] Chebyshev (1874) in connection with research on limit theorems.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] Then there is a sequence ${\mu _{n}}'$ that weakly converges to a distribution function $\mu$ having $\alpha _{k}$ as its moments.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] If the moments determine $\mu$ uniquely, then the sequence ${\mu _{n}}'$ weakly converges to $\mu$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] Partial moments are sometimes referred to as "one-sided moments".
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] If the integral function does not converge, the partial moment does not exist.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] Partial moments are normalized by being raised to the power 1/*n*.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] The upside potential ratio may be expressed as a ratio of a first-order upper partial moment to a normalized second-order lower partial moment.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] Let (*M*, *d*) be a metric space, and let B(*M*) be the Borel σ-algebra on *M*, the σ-algebra generated by the *d*-open subsets of *M*.
[src:adam-optimizer/moment-mathematics] (For technical reasons, it is also convenient to assume that *M* is a separable space with respect to the metric *d*.) Let 1 ≤ *p* ≤ ∞.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] The basic idea behind stochastic approximation can be traced back to the Robbins–Monro algorithm of the 1950s.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Today, stochastic gradient descent has become an important optimization method in machine learning.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Both statistical estimation and machine learning consider the problem of minimizing an objective function that has the form of a sum: $Q(w)={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}Q_{i}(w),$ where the parameter w that minimizes $Q(w)$ is to be estimated.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Each summand function $Q_{i}$ is typically associated with the i -th observation in the data set (used for training).
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In classical statistics, sum-minimization problems arise in least squares and in maximum-likelihood estimation (for independent observations).
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] The general class of estimators that arise as minimizers of sums are called M-estimators.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, in statistics, it has been long recognized that requiring even local minimization is too restrictive for some problems of maximum-likelihood estimation.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Therefore, contemporary statistical theorists often consider stationary points of the likelihood function (or zeros of its derivative, the score function, and other estimating equations).
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] The sum-minimization problem also arises for empirical risk minimization.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] There, $Q_{i}(w)$ is the value of the loss function at i -th example, and $Q(w)$ is the empirical risk.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In many cases, the summand functions have a simple form that enables inexpensive evaluations of the sum-function and the sum gradient.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] For example, in statistics, one-parameter exponential families allow economical function-evaluations and gradient-evaluations.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, in other cases, evaluating the sum-gradient may require expensive evaluations of the gradients from all summand functions.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] When the training set is enormous and no simple formulas exist, evaluating the sums of gradients becomes very expensive, because evaluating the gradient requires evaluating all the summand functions' gradients.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] To economize on the computational cost at every iteration, stochastic gradient descent samples a subset of summand functions at every step.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is very effective in the case of large-scale machine learning problems.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In stochastic (or "on-line") gradient descent, the true gradient of $Q(w)$ is approximated by a gradient at a single sample: $w:=w-\eta \,\nabla Q_{i}(w).$ As the algorithm sweeps through the training set, it performs the above update for each training sample.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Several passes can be made over the training set until the algorithm converges.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] If this is done, the data can be shuffled for each pass to prevent cycles.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Typical implementations may use an adaptive learning rate so that the algorithm converges.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] A compromise between computing the true gradient and the gradient at a single sample is to compute the gradient against more than one training sample (called a "mini-batch") at each step.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] This can perform significantly better than "true" stochastic gradient descent described, because the code can make use of vectorization libraries rather than computing each step separately as was first shown in where it was called "the bunch-mode back-propagation algorithm".
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] It may also result in smoother convergence, as the gradient computed at each step is averaged over more training samples.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] The convergence of stochastic gradient descent has been analyzed using the theories of convex minimization and of stochastic approximation.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is in fact a consequence of the Robbins–Siegmund theorem.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is the key difference between stochastic gradient descent and batched gradient descent.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In general, given a linear regression ${\hat {y}}=\sum _{k\in 1:m}w_{k}x_{k}$ problem, stochastic gradient descent behaves differently when $m<n$ (underparameterized) and $m\geq n$ (overparameterized).
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In the overparameterized case, stochastic gradient descent converges to $\arg \min _{w:w^{T}x_{k}=y_{k}\forall k\in 1:n}\|w-w_{0}\|$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] That is, SGD converges to the interpolation solution with minimum distance from the starting $w_{0}$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is true even when the learning rate remains constant.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In the underparameterized case, SGD does not converge if learning rate remains constant.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In 1951, Herbert Robbins and Sutton Monro introduced the earliest stochastic approximation methods, preceding stochastic gradient descent.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Building on this work one year later, Jack Kiefer and Jacob Wolfowitz published an optimization algorithm very close to stochastic gradient descent, using central differences as an approximation of the gradient.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Later in the 1950s, Frank Rosenblatt used SGD to optimize his perceptron model, demonstrating the first applicability of stochastic gradient descent to neural networks.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Backpropagation was first described in 1986, with stochastic gradient descent being used to efficiently optimize parameters across neural networks with multiple hidden layers.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Soon after, another improvement was developed: mini-batch gradient descent, where small batches of data are substituted for single samples.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In 1997, the practical performance benefits from vectorization achievable with such small batches were first explored, paving the way for efficient optimization in machine learning.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] As of 2023, this mini-batch approach remains the norm for training neural networks, balancing the benefits of stochastic gradient descent with gradient descent.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] By the 1980s, momentum had already been introduced, and was added to SGD optimization techniques in 1986.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, these optimization techniques assumed constant hyperparameters, i.e. a fixed learning rate and momentum parameter.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In the 2010s, adaptive approaches to applying SGD with a per-parameter learning rate were introduced with AdaGrad (for "Adaptive Gradient") in 2011 and RMSprop (for "Root Mean Square Propagation") in 2012.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In 2014, Adam (for "Adaptive Moment Estimation") was published, applying the adaptive approaches of RMSprop to momentum; many improvements and branches of Adam were then developed such as Adadelta, Adagrad, AdamW, and Adamax.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Within machine learning, approaches to optimization in 2023 are dominated by Adam-derived optimizers, TensorFlow and PyTorch, by far the most popular machine learning libraries, as of 2023 largely only include Adam-derived optimizers, as well as predecessors to Adam such as RMSprop and classic SGD.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] PyTorch also partially supports limited-memory BFGS, a line-search method, but only for single-device setups without parameter groups.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Stochastic gradient descent is a popular algorithm for training a wide range of models in machine learning, including (linear) support vector machines, logistic regression (see, e.g., Vowpal Wabbit) and graphical models.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] When combined with the backpropagation algorithm, it is the *de facto* standard algorithm for training artificial neural networks.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Its use has been also reported in the Geophysics community, specifically to applications of Full Waveform Inversion (FWI).
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Stochastic gradient descent competes with the L-BFGS algorithm, which is also widely used.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Stochastic gradient descent has been used since at least 1960 for training linear regression models, originally under the name ADALINE.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Another stochastic gradient descent algorithm is the least mean squares (LMS) adaptive filter.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Many improvements on the basic stochastic gradient descent algorithm have been proposed and used.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In particular, in machine learning, the need to set a learning rate (step size) has been recognized as problematic.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Setting this parameter too high can cause the algorithm to diverge; setting it too low makes it slow to converge.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] A conceptually simple extension of stochastic gradient descent makes the learning rate a decreasing function ηt of the iteration number t, giving a *learning rate schedule*, so that the first iterations cause large changes in the parameters, while the later ones do only fine-tuning.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Such schedules have been known since the work of MacQueen on k-means clustering.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Practical guidance on choosing the step size in several variants of SGD is given by Spall.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] As mentioned earlier, classical stochastic gradient descent is generally sensitive to learning rate η.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Fast convergence requires large learning rates but this may induce numerical instability.
