[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Although theoretical convergence of this procedure happens under relatively mild assumptions, in practice the procedure can be quite unstable.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In particular, when $\eta$ is misspecified so that $I-\eta x_{i}x_{i}'$ has large absolute eigenvalues with high probability, the procedure may diverge numerically within a few iterations.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] This procedure will remain numerically stable virtually for all $\eta$ as the learning rate is now normalized.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Such comparison between classical and implicit stochastic gradient descent in the least squares problem is very similar to the comparison between least mean squares (LMS) and normalized least mean squares filter (NLMS).
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Even though a closed-form solution for ISGD is only possible in least squares, the procedure can be efficiently implemented in a wide range of models.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Specifically, suppose that $Q_{i}(w)$ depends on w only through a linear combination with features $x_{i}$ , so that we can write $\nabla _{w}Q_{i}(w)=-q(x_{i}'w)x_{i}$ , where $q()\in \mathbb {R}$ may depend on $x_{i},y_{i}$ as well but not on w except through $x_{i}'w$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Least squares obeys this rule, and so does logistic regression, and most generalized linear models.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In such settings, ISGD is simply implemented as follows.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] The scaling factor $\xi ^{\ast }\in \mathbb {R}$ can be found through the bisection method since in most regular models, such as the aforementioned generalized linear models, function $q()$ is decreasing, and thus the search bounds for $\xi ^{\ast }$ are $[\min(0,f(0)),\max(0,f(0))]$ .
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Further proposals include the *momentum method* or the *heavy ball method*, which in ML context appeared in Rumelhart, Hinton and Williams' paper on backpropagation learning and borrowed the idea from Soviet mathematician Boris Polyak's 1964 article on solving functional equations.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] The name momentum stems from an analogy to momentum in physics: the weight vector w , thought of as a particle traveling through parameter space, incurs acceleration from the gradient of the loss ("force").
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Unlike in classical stochastic gradient descent, it tends to keep traveling in the same direction, preventing oscillations.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Momentum has been used successfully by computer scientists in the training of artificial neural networks for several decades.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] The *momentum method* is closely related to underdamped Langevin dynamics, and may be combined with simulated annealing.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] In mid-1980s the method was modified by Yurii Nesterov to use the gradient predicted at the next point, and the resulting so-called *Nesterov Accelerated Gradient* was sometimes used in ML in the 2010s.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] ${\bar {w}}={\frac {1}{t}}\sum _{i=0}^{t-1}w_{i}.$ When optimization is done, this averaged parameter vector takes the place of w.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] where $g_{\tau }=\nabla Q_{i}(w)$ , the gradient, at iteration τ.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] $G_{j,j}=\sum _{\tau =1}^{t}g_{\tau ,j}^{2}.$ This vector essentially stores a historical sum of gradient squares by dimension and is updated after every iteration.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] The formula for an update is now $w:=w-\eta \,\mathrm {diag} (G)^{-{\frac {1}{2}}}\odot g$ or, written as per-parameter updates, $w_{j}:=w_{j}-{\frac {\eta }{\sqrt {G_{j,j}}}}g_{j}.$ Each {*G*(*i*,*i*)} gives rise to a scaling factor for the learning rate that applies to a single parameter *w**i*.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] Since the denominator in this factor, ${\textstyle {\sqrt {G_{i}}}={\sqrt {\sum _{\tau =1}^{t}g_{\tau }^{2}}}}$ is the *ℓ*2 norm of previous derivatives, extreme parameter updates get dampened, while parameters that get few or small updates receive higher learning rates.
[src:adam-optimizer/stochastic-gradient-descent] While designed for convex problems, AdaGrad has been successfully applied to non-convex optimization.
